{
  "texts": [
    "Photon absorption takes place when these photons possess energy equal to or greater than the bandgap energy of the semiconductor material within the cell (Najm et al., 2023).",
    "Subsequently, the absorbed photons transfer their energy to electrons, elevating them from the valence band to the conduction band and generating electronhole pairs within the material.",
    "Capitalizing on the internal electric field within the semiconductor, the newly formed electron-hole pairs undergo separation, with electrons migrating toward the n-type (negative) side and holes toward the p-type (positive) side.",
    "This separation initiates the flow of electrical current-a movement of electrons and holes-ultimately harnessed as electricity.",
    "The conductive metal contacts on the solar cell's surface collect this electrical current, rendering it available for various applications (Song et al., 2023)."
  ]
}